<DOC><DOCNO> AP900226-0092 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-90 1414EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Perrier     02-26 0155</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Perrier,0161</SECOND><HEAD>Perrier Says Its Recall Nearly Complete</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Perrier said Monday the recall of the 160 millionbottles of sparkling water it had on the market around the worldwas more than 90 percent complete.   Withdrawing of Perrier's familiar green bottles began Feb. 14when the water was found to contain the chemical benzene.   The company said a redistribution plan is being developed anddetails will be announced.   The recall was estimated to put a $35 million dent in Perrier'sprofits.   Perrier said the problem that prompted the recall had beenisolated at the gas filtration level of production.   ``New procedures have been put in place to assure qualitycontrol: double filtration of carbonic gas, tests for hydrocarboncontent, as well as continuous surveillance by an externallaboratory,'' Perrier said.   It said that after tests by independent experts, nocontamination or pollution of the company's spring in Vergeze hasbeen found.</TEXT></DOC>